    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘A House of Dynamite’",
      "note": "great for an hour, then the balloon deflates",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "A House of Dynamite",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Kathryn Bigelow's first film in eight years, written by Noah Oppenheim, on Netflix. A single ICBM of unknown origin flies at Chicago and the movie replays the same real-time 18 minutes through the White House Situation Room, NSA, Pentagon, Fort Greeley and Stratcom. Idris Elba as the president, Rebecca Ferguson, Gabriel Basso, Jared Harris, Tracy Letts, Anthony Ramos, Greta Lee, Moses Ingram. Amanda saw it at Venice and was gripped; Sean saw a Netflix screening and soured. Both agree the first third is superb and the film 'doesn't land the plane': Elba is miscast (a body double takes his jump shot), the Gettysburg and save-the-elephants metaphors are laid on thick, and the abrupt final image (Ramos collapsing outside Fort Greeley) drew open laughter at the New York Film Festival."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Adam Naiman on ‘The Mastermind’",
      "guest": "Adam Naiman on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Mastermind",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Kelly Reichardt's new film (the first she's written solo since 'River of Grass') with Josh O'Connor as a dissatisfied 1970 Framingham dad who decides to become an art thief and is terrible at it. Naiman calls the title ironic and the film very funny about male vanity and solipsism, set against Watergate and Vietnam; Sean reads it as Reichardt answering critics who say nothing happens in her movies. All three prefer it to 'A House of Dynamite.' John Magaro, Gaby Hoffmann, Bill Camp, Hope Davis, Alana Haim."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
